-- 
Ukraine Has Smaller Share of Weak Winter Grains, Ministry Says

-- B y   D a r y n a   K r a s n o l u t s k a
-- 
2011-02-21T12:42:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-21/ukraine-has-smaller-share-of-weak-winter-grains-ministry-says.html
The portion of Ukrainian winter-
grain plants in weak condition declined in the week ended Feb.
18, the Agriculture Ministry said, citing regional data.  Plants classified as weak fell to 5.9 percent of the crop
from 6.2 percent a week earlier, the ministry said today in a
statement on its website. Weak winter wheat dropped to 5.7
percent from 5.9 percent, it said.  Winter grains were planted across 8.09 million hectares (20
million acres), with winter wheat covering 6.55 million
hectares, the figures showed. Grains in good condition came to
56.5 percent, and those judged to be satisfactory accounted for
37.6 percent.  Winter wheat in good condition came to 57.7 percent, with
36.6 percent classified as satisfactory, according to the
statement. Winter barley in good condition amounted to 47.3
percent, while 44.4 percent was satisfactory and 8.4 percent was
weak.  About 52.7 percent of rapeseed was in good condition and
39.1 percent was satisfactory, while 8.2 percent was deemed
weak.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Daryna Krasnolutska in Kiev at 
 dkrasnolutsk@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Willy Morris at   wmorris@bloomberg.net  